  1. What is the proportion of taxa included in this study? Show a table and plot that reflects this count.
deserts %>%
  tabyl(taxa) 
##     taxa     n      percent
##     Bird   450 0.0129362387
##   Rabbit    75 0.0021560398
##  Reptile    14 0.0004024608
##   Rodent 34247 0.9845052607
deserts %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxa))+
  geom_bar(aes(y = after_stat(count)/sum(after_stat(count))))+ 
  labs(title="Taxa Percentage",
       x="Taxa",
       y="Percentage")+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)+
  coord_flip()

  1. For the taxa included in the study, use the fill option to show the proportion of individuals sampled by plot_type.
deserts %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxa,fill = plot_type))+
  geom_bar()+ 
  labs(title="Taxa Abundance",
       x="Taxa",
       y="Percentage")+
  coord_flip()

  1. Dipodomys merriami is the most frequently sampled animal in the study. How have the number of observations of this species changed over the years included in the study?
deserts %>%
  filter(species == "merriami") %>%
  group_by(year)  %>%
  summarise(n_species=n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=n_species))+
  geom_point()+
  labs(title="Population Changes of Marriami over Year",
       x="Year",
       y="Population")

  1. Which two species have, on average, the highest weight? Once you have identified them, make a new column that is a ratio of weight to hindfoot_length. Make a plot that shows the range of this new ratio and fill by sex.
deserts %>%
  group_by(species) %>%
  summarise(mean_weight = mean(weight, na.rm = T)) %>%
  arrange(-mean_weight)
